  <section class="morph-highlights" aria-labelledby="morph-highlights-title">
    <h2 id="morph-highlights-title" class="morph-highlights-title">Five ideas from the chapter</h2>
    <p class="morph-highlights-intro">
      These are the chapter’s through-lines for teachers—not section titles. Each one is illustrated somewhere in the
      trees above.
    </p>
    <ol class="morph-concept-list">
      <li class="morph-concept">
        <h3 class="morph-concept-name">Morpheme</h3>
        <p>
          The <strong>smallest unit</strong> with meaning or grammatical work. Words can be <strong>simple</strong> (one
          morpheme, e.g. <em>happy</em>) or <strong>complex</strong> (e.g. <em>teacher</em> = <em>teach</em> +
          <em>-er</em>). <strong>Syllables ≠ morphemes.</strong>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="morph-concept">
        <h3 class="morph-concept-name">Root and affix</h3>
        <p>
          The <strong>root</strong> carries the core meaning; <strong>affixes</strong> attach as
          <strong>prefixes</strong> or <strong>suffixes</strong>. <strong>Compounds</strong> glue whole words together
          (e.g. <em>hallway</em>, <em>rainbow</em>). The chapter also shows <strong>infixes</strong> and
          <strong>circumfixes</strong> in other languages so English isn’t the whole story.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="morph-concept">
        <h3 class="morph-concept-name">Free, bound, content, function</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Free morphemes</strong> stand alone; <strong>bound morphemes</strong> must attach.
          <strong>Content</strong> morphemes fill open classes (nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs);
          <strong>function</strong> morphemes belong to small closed classes (articles, prepositions, pronouns).
          <strong>Bound roots</strong> (e.g. in <em>inept</em>) remind us that not every stem is a free word.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="morph-concept">
        <h3 class="morph-concept-name">Derivation vs. inflection</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>Derivational</strong> affixes build new words (often changing class or meaning) and are not required
          by syntax. <strong>Inflectional</strong> suffixes mark grammar (plural <em>-s</em>, tense <em>-ed</em>, etc.),
          stay on the <strong>outer edge</strong>, and don’t change basic word class. Order matters:
          derivation tends to sit <strong>inside</strong> inflection.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li class="morph-concept">
        <h3 class="morph-concept-name">Allomorphs, analysis, teaching</h3>
        <p>
          Morphemes have <strong>predictable surface variants</strong> (e.g. plural <em>-s</em>, past <em>-ed</em>,
          <em>a</em> ~ <em>an</em>). <strong>Structure</strong> can differ even when spelling matches—compare the two
          <em>unlockable</em> trees. For classrooms: make <strong>word families</strong> and affix meanings explicit so
          learners recognize patterns in new vocabulary.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p class="morph-source-line">
      <strong>Source:</strong> Park-Johnson, S., &amp; Shin, S. J. (2020). <em>Linguistics for Language Teachers</em>.
      Taylor &amp; Francis. ·
      <strong>Further reading:</strong> Aronoff, M., &amp; Fudeman, K. (2010). <em>What is morphology?</em> (2nd ed.).
      Wiley-Blackwell.
    </p>
